mpacts of decentralisation. The authors explore, in interdisciplinary and multi-level perspectives, continuity and change in regulating and practicing collective bargaining in France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, the Netherlands, Poland, Spain and Sweden. In cross-country comparisons, company case studies in manufacturing and retail show the divergent effects of national regimes and social partners' power resources on trade unions' strategies and influence in company bargaining.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollective bargainingzEuropean Union countriesvCase studies. 0aCollective bargainingzEuropean Union countries. 0aLabor unionszEuropean Union countries. 0aWageszEuropean Union countries. 4aContemporary Society. 4aEconomics and Finance. 4aPolitics and Government. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aLabour relations, Trade unions, Collective bargaining.1 aArmaroli, Ilaria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCzarzasty, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaipeter, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIossa, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJansen, Niels, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahmann, Marcus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuñoz Ruiz, Ana Belén, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaolucci, Valentina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRamos Martín, Nuria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosenbohm, Soph